              "content": "# PEMBERTON RFQ — EXECUTIVE SUMMARY\n**One-Page Brief for Commercial Sponsor Call**\n\n---\n\n## DEAL AT A GLANCE\n- **Customer:** Pemberton Engineering (UK manufacturer, 3 industrial sites)\n- **Scope:** Indirect MRO supply framework — 1,247 SKUs across 7 categories (tools, fasteners, fluids, PPE, electrical, pneumatics, spares)\n- **Value:** £18.4m indicative annual spend (non-binding)\n- **Term:** 3 years + optional 2-year extension\n- **Bid Due:** [DATE from invitation letter]\n\n---\n\n## RED FLAGS — 3 CRITICAL ISSUES\n\n| Issue | Impact | Our Ask |\n|-------|--------|---------|\n| **30-Day Termination** | Pemberton can exit with 30 days' notice, any time. We absorb £500k–£1m setup costs with no recovery. | 90-day notice OR demob cost reimbursement |\n| **Unlimited IP Indemnity** | Contractual indemnity for IP claims (no fault required) is uncapped & uninsurable. Single patent-troll suit = £1m+ exposure with no cap. | Cap indemnity at 12-month fees; add claim control |\n| **Aggressive Price Pressure** | Benchmarking (any time, any competitor) + open-book costing (top-50 SKUs) + margin compression = margin erosion spiral. | 1x/year benchmarking; exclude new entrants; 15% materiality gate |\n\n---\n\n## FINANCIAL IMPACT\n\n### Scenario 1: \"No Redlines\" (Current Terms)\n- Blended margin target: 8% (£1.47m profit, 3-year)\n- Benchmarking + margin compression risk: Margin compresses to 5–6%\n- Termination risk cost (PV): ~£300k (probability-weighted setup loss if exit year 1)\n- **Net profit: £850k–£1m** | **ROI: 15–18%** (acceptable but risky)\n\n### Scenario 2: \"All Redlines Accepted\"\n- Blended margin: 8% (maintained)\n- Benchmarking risk: Capped at 1x/year; materiality gate limits erosion to <1%\n- Termination risk: Insurable; demob reimbursement covers £500k setup\n- **Net profit: £1.4m** | **ROI: 25–30%** (strong)\n\n### Scenario 3: \"Pemberton Refuses All Redlines\"\n- Margin erosion risk: 37% (8% → 5%)\n- Uninsured indemnity exposure: £1m+ unhedged\n- Termination risk: £500k+ uncompensated loss on year-1 exit\n- **Net profit: £600k–£700k** | **ROI: 12–15%** (marginal; consider walk)\n\n---\n\n## RECOMMENDED STRATEGY\n\n**Phase 1 (Before Bid — If Clarification Window Open):**\n- Email Pemberton procurement: \"Attached is our redlined MSA addressing alignment on three commercial terms.\"\n- Frame as: \"We're interested in this framework and want to surface these early so there are no surprises.\"\n- **Benefit:** Shows sophistication; gives Pemberton 10+ days to respond before final bid.\n\n**Phase 2 (Bid Response):**\n- Submit marked-up MSA with all three redlines + one-page rationale for each.\n- Rationale should be *business-neutral*, not legal-defensive:\n  - Termination: \"We need 90 days to work off inventory on a £18.4m framework with no volume floor.\"\n  - Indemnity: \"Contractual IP indemnification requires insurable cap. Current terms are uninsurable.\"\n  - Benchmarking: \"Annual benchmarking with materiality gate gives pricing stability for 3-year ramp.\"\n\n**Phase 3 (Shortlist Negotiation):**\n- Fallback order: Benchmarking > Termination > Indemnity\n  - **Benchmarking:** Most negotiable; Pemberton might accept 2x/year if we move on materiality.\n  - **Termination:** Show them breakeven analysis; if concurrent orders >£500k/month, we can live with 60-day notice.\n  - **Indemnity:** Non-negotiable; tie to insurance coverage. If carrier won't insure, we can't absorb risk.\n\n---\n\n## DECISION POINTS FOR SPONSOR\n\n**1. Do we redline all three or pick our battles?**  \n→ Start with all three. Worst case, we concede benchmarking and hold termination + indemnity.\n\n**2. What's our walk-away?**  \n→ If Pemberton refuses indemnity cap AND insurance won't cover it, we cannot bid. Full stop.  \n→ If Pemberton refuses demob reimbursement AND concurrent orders forecast <£500k/month, recommend walk.\n\n**3. Should we test Pemberton before final bid?**  \n→ **Yes.** Use clarification window. Shows we've done homework; gives Pemberton time to brief their commercial team.\n\n**4. What's our fallback bid price if redlines fail?**  \n→ Increase blended margin 2–3% to absorb unpriced risk. Makes bid uncompetitive; likely loses on scoring.\n\n---\n\n## NEXT STEPS\n\n1. **Today/Tomorrow:** Secure your approval to proceed with redlines (all three or subset).\n2. **If clarification window open:** Email Pemberton within 48 hours with marked MSA.\n3. **1 week before bid:** Confirm insurance carrier can quote on capped indemnity; get preliminary quote.\n4. **Final bid:** Submit redlined documents + one-page rationale per redline.\n\n---\n\n**Prepared by:** [Commercial Legal]  \n**Approved by:** [GC]  \n**Escalation contact:** [Commercial Sponsor]\n\n**Questions? Schedule 15-min call to discuss fallback positions and walk-away thresholds.**\n"
